social_posts.post_text: With all my travel, I haven’t been able to hit the courts as much as I’d like!😬 So lately any time I get to hit, my focus has been on finding my timing, moving my feet, and getting in a rhythm. What helps me is early racket preparation, getting to shots early, and shot placement/depth rather than speed. What are you guys working on in your game?🎾 Tell me🥰👇
Happy Friday!🥰🎾 What are you guys up to this weekend? It’s the holiday season 🎁 and I have something so exciting to share with you all next week, I can’t wait!😍

Ok it’s getting too cold to play outside🤣❄️☃️ I get asked a lot what my favorite court surface to play on is. I love them all, and the different movement, ball bounce, and adjustments you have to make for each surface. But for me, it’s a fast, hard indoor court😍 No elements, and it feels/sounds like you are hitting every ball insanely hard😂🎾So yes, I’m excited for indoor tennis season😁 What’s your fav surface?

Five years ago, I had so many different thoughts and ideas about the game that I wanted to share with the world. I began writing different articles and blogs on fashion in tennis, comparing tennis players to their basketball player counterparts, various stories about the game, and much more. I wanted an organized place to share all of my ideas, so I hired a website designer. I published my articles there, which were well-received and appreciated by so many. I am always so grateful for the opportunities that came from that!

Since then, my life has been a whirlwind of different jobs and roles in professional tennis. I’ve traveled and worked with so many tournaments worldwide and partnered with some of the best tennis companies and brands in the industry. My career has been an exciting journey, and this year has been the best one yet!😍

All this to say- I am having a full circle moment here- I’ve been working very hard on a project that I am very excited to share with you all finally. As so much has changed in the past five years, I have entirely recreated and relaunched my website. I am so excited to share my journey with you all through travel updates/newsletters, partnership highlights, and even some fun merch items available😍

As always, thank you all so much for the support, and I can’t wait for you to see and enjoy it! It’s going to be a crazy 2023, and I am taking you guys along for the ride with me😉 LINK IN BIO😍🎾

Going to start sharing more instructional vids😍 starting with inside out and inside in forehands.🎾 Dominating the court with your forehand requires you to be comfortable hitting different targets with a variety of spin and depth out of your backhand corner.

This is Nick Kyrgios’ “3 Spot Run Around Forehand” @topcourt drill. It’ll help you develop your run around forehand and put the pressure on your opponent.

Give it a try and start running your opponent side to side by taking control of your inside out/inside in forehands😉🎾🔝🟨

I used to not be excited to work on my weaknesses until I realized I could use them to set up my strengths😊

Check out @alexzverev123’s “Backhand to Forehand Set Up” @topcourt drill, where you can use your backhand cross court to set up a heavy forehand🔥

With patience, anticipation, and quick decision making on the backhand side, pay attention and watch for the right shot to move around and step in and crank the forehand. Ironically, I do this more on the forehand side (and watch for the backhand) because my backhand is my best shot. 2023 we’re taking control of the points we play lol😍 Give it a try!🎾🔝🟨

Time to hit the court again!👀😍🎾 We all know @casperruud’s game is inspired by @rafaelnadal. This might be one of the most Rafa drills of all time😂🙌

Get your feet and inside-out forehands going with Casper’s “2 Ball Forehand Domination” @topcourt drill, where the first step to the ball and first step in recovery are the most important and will give you time to prepare and find space. 

Remember that a dominant forehand starts with good movement, and realistic patterns like this one is key to finding rhythm and confidence in points😍 HAVE FUN🎾
What a great rack-et!🙂🎾

Time for some instruction: Indian Wells Edition😍🌴☀️

Improve your backhand consistency and change in direction with @bnpparibasopen defending champ @taylor_fritz and his “Backhand Red Light Green Light” @topcourt drill🎾

Get in a rhythm with some cross court backhands, and when you see the right ball (and it feels right) step in and rip it up the line💥

Remember to be patient when choosing which shot to attack. The backhand down the line is my favorite shot, so this is one of my favorite drills!🙌

The backhand down the line is my fav shot. I wish I would have used this drill more when I was competing to set myself up!

This @alexzverev123 “Slice to Backhand Down the Line” @topcourt drill teaches you to use your slice to create opportunities and get comfortable going from a slice to a topspin or flat backhand. 

It’s also a great way to practice neutralizing the point then attacking.

Your slice could be your new weapon, not only to throw your opponent off with different spin but to create an offensive ball for you to slam down the line for a winner. And if that shot isn’t a winner, the next one probably will be😉

Five reasons why I’m obsessed with the @u.t.s_tour:
1) The overall environment- a DJ playing music the entire time, fans cheering/walking to their seats whenever they want, the players engaging with the crowd
2) I’ve never seen a tennis match/event where fans were attentive and excited the ENTIRE time
3) Loved watching the pros show their fun and hilarious personalities in ways they wouldn’t be able to during traditional tennis matches
4) The format: 6 matches a day, four 8-minute quarters, one serve, three point bonus card, no warm up.. among other things… it was fast paced and the perfect amount of tennis 
5) How great this is for the sport. The tour schedule is long and serious. This is a perfect small break in the calendar for players to have some fun and also great prize $. Also in this day and age attention spans are short. UTS makes tennis fun and fast paced in a way thats easy and interactive for general sports fans to digest and get/stay excited about the game.

@patrickmouratoglou is a mastermind. Grateful to have been a part of Ultimate Tennis Showdown LA, and looking forward to the future UTS events!🎾🔥💥

For the most part, professional tennis is an unbelievable enterprise. But I’ve been around the game long enough to see the inconsistencies, conflicts of interest, and lack of clarity across the board in professional tennis. If I can help my friends on tour by using my voice and platform to bring attention and push for improvements on the important topics then I’m going to do that. 

It was a pleasure sitting down with the @ptpaplayers to talk about the tough topics that our sport needs help with. Having this player association (spearheaded by @djokernole and @vasek.pospisil) is important. The mission, principles, and voices of the PTPA is entirely necessary and something the sport desperately needs in order for the important changes to be made. 

I love highlighting the beauty of professional tennis, but also want to help push the game forward to a more fair and opportunistic tour for all the amazing players involved. 

#PTPA #PTPAplayers

Hii friends🙋🏻‍♀️🥰 With the final Grand Slam of the year coming and going, this can be a confusing time for tennis fans- lots going on with different players all over the world. Here are some of the exciting tournaments and events from this past week and upcoming👀:

2) Guadalajara Open: Not too often you see a lone WTA 1000 (with no ATP Masters 1000 counterpart) 💕🇲🇽
3) Ultimate Tennis Showdown: The 2nd UTS event of the year in Frankfurt just wrapped up and further proved that the fan-friendly format is an absolute hit⚡️
4) Tournaments in Asia: Many players traveled to China and Japan for a series of tournaments. The China Open Masters 1000 starts next week 🇨🇳

Instruction time!🤩🎾 Today we’re focusing on footwork by doing the “Forehand Spot Footwork” drill. For tall players like me, developing proper footwork to be efficient with movement is crucial. This drill specifically helps with creating proper spacing and footwork for your forehand.
1. Start slow, then build speed and intensity
2. Focus on the footwork, not the ball
3. Exaggerate the anchor and recovery step 
4. Keep the footwork precise and clean
The forehand is my weaker side, so I always make sure to practice drills like this to build confidence. Give it a try, and tag me if you do!🥰🎾

Brace yourself.. not my usual post🤣 but wanted to share a life update- not too long ago I was in a car wreck. I underwent anterior cervical disc replacement surgery to remove the C5-C6 disc in my neck and replace it with an artificial disc. I’m extremely thankful to my surgeon @drkimspinemd and the entire New York City @hspecialsurgery staff for taking the best care of me and making this process as successful as possible. 

As I begin the healing process and physical therapy journey, I’m feeling encouraged, determined, and eager to lean into some qualities that I haven’t tapped into since my competitive playing career 10 years ago.🎾 Thanking God for a successful surgery🙏🙏🙏  And a huge thank you to my amazing family and friends, and everyone who reached out and kept my spirits up. This isn’t a setback! It’s just all part of the comeback and I can’t wait to be feeling 100% again!❤️
